2025 is shaping up to be a record year (\$117bn, up 14% y/y), setting a tough comp for 2026. However, we expect TSMC & DRAM to drive 5% growth to \$122bn.

What's Changed? We've revised our 2025 WFE forecast from \$109bn (up 6% y/y) to \$117bn (up 14%) and our 2026 forecast from \$110bn (up 1% y/y) to \$122bn (up 5%). Our 2025 revision is driven by NAND and logic, while our 2026 revision is driven by DRAM, leading- edge logic, and China.

2025 a Record Year. We estimate 2025 WFE will reach \$117bn (+14% y/y) as China, NAND, and DRAM are all tracking far stronger than expected. Initially, we anticipated 2025 to be a digestion year with declines in China and DRAM following record WFE in 2024, but shipments have exceeded expectations for both end- markets. We model LAM (+35%), KLA (+17%) and ASML (+16%) to outperform WFE with LAM's outperformance driven by NAND & China, KLA by DRAM, and ASML by foundry logic.

How strong can the 2026 drivers be? Despite tough y/y comps, we expect customers with secular end- market growth (TSMC, DRAM) to continue spending, offsetting areas of weakness (Intel, TXN). We focus on the growth drivers as areas of weakness are well understood. Our views on the growth drivers into 2026 are: 1) DRAM: We model 10% y/y growth as leading- edge greenfield should accelerate driven by Samsung and Hynix. 2) TSMC: WFE mix of capex normalizing back to 80% could drive equipment upside on a flat \$4Obn headline capex. 3) Leading- edge logic: Intel and Samsung reaccelerating foundry investment is the biggest upside risk to our forecast.

Continue to prefer TSMC, gxposure & China local, DRAM > NAND. Our global SPE preferences through the first half of the year had been TSMC exposure (ASML, KLA, SCREEN), China local (Naura, AMEC), and NAND (MKS, Kokusai). We maintain our positive view on TSMC exposure and China local but shift our preference from NAND to DRAM as we expect stronger WFE growth for DRAM. The biggest risks to our WFE view are: 1) Intel & Samsung: Both companies reaccelerating their foundry aspirations is by far the biggest upside risk to estimates. 2) China restrictions: Technology restrictions that would limit mature logic equipment to China is the largest downside risk. 3) DRAM cycle: HBM pricing pressure weighing on margin and dampening investment appetite is the second largest downside risk.

2025 WFE up \(14\%\) y/y, a record year. We estimate 2025 WFE will come in at \(\) 117bn\(+14\% y / y\) as China, NAND, and DRAM are all tracking far stronger than expected. We initially anticipated 2025 to be a digestion year with China and DRAM to decline y/y following record WFE in 2024, but shipments have tracked far stronger than expected for both end- markets. We outline areas that came in stronger than expected:

China (2025 \(\) 39.7bn\(- 4\% y / y\)): Western equipment companies had entered the year guiding for China revenue to decline \(20\%\) y/y but upticked through the year. Shipments have varied by player, with LAM seeing record China in the JunQ and guided for a sequential increase into the SepQ while Tokyo Electron's 1H was \(16\%\) below 2024 run rate. We had highlighted this dynamic of stronger China demand in Semiconductor Capital Equipment: Mid 2Q'25 WFE Update, China Uptick (1 Jul 2025), and while our overall numbers have come in- line, strength has varied by company.

NAND (2025 \(\) 10.2bn\(+\) 102\% y / y\)): LAM and TEL started seeing an uptick in NAND shipments from the DecQ 2024 as customers looked to upgrade capacity from 1XX to 2XX. Growth accelerated through the 1H as customers upgraded capacity to meet eSSD demand (necessitates 2XX layer QLC) and due to competitive reasons (Samsung, Kioxia, and YMTC resumed spending). These drivers contributed towards combined AMAT/LAM/TEL's NAND shipments more than tripling from the lows (JunQ 25 vs SepQ 24).

DRAM (2025 \(\) 29.7bn\(+\) 1\% y / y\)): Following a record 2024 ( \(\) 29.3bn\(+\) 50\% y / y\) driven by greenfield, we anticipated 2025 to be a digestion year as the industry continues to invest into greenfield but not at the pace it did in 2024 (2024 Greenfield MSe 203kwpm vs 2020- 2023 average 150kwpm). As we outlined in Semiconductor Capital Equipment: 2Q'25 WFE update, Rethinking our DRAM Thesis (22 May 2025), we had underestimated yield issues from increased EUV adoption and the equipment mix shift towards lithography and process control, which lead to stronger than anticipated DRAM WFE.

Leading- edge logic came broadly in- line with our expectation as TSMC is tracking towards their \(\) 40bn\(capex guide for 2025. Intel's 2025 capex is stronger than expected as the company's revised approach towards 14A development being dependent on customer commitments impacts capex from 2026 (and orders in 2025).

LAM the winner in 2025, followed by KLA & ASML. We estimate Core- 5 shipments to be up \(13\% y / y\) in 2025 vs WFE up \(14\%\) , and model LAM \((+35\%)\) , KLA \((+17\%)\) and ASML \((+16\%)\) to outperform WFE. LAM's outperformance is driven by 2 areas: 1) NAND: We model 2025 y/y growth to come below AMAT/TEL/KLA \((+77\% v s +116\%)\) , but LAM is by far the biggest market share holder and the only company where NAND is large enough to materially move total shipments. 2) China: We model LAM's China revenue to increase \(20\% y / y\) (systems \(+32\% y / y\) ) vs Western players ex- LAM down \(20\%\) as the company benefits from Hua Hong & Huali's strong investment in the 2H, wins with newer provincial projects, and NAND upgrade spending at Samsung's Xi'an fab. KLA's outperformance was led by DRAM where we model revenue growth of \(27\%\) vs DRAM WFE growth of \(2\%\) , and we model ASML's foundry logic shipments to grow \(28\% y / y\) vs foundry logic WFE growth of \(12\%\)

MS View: 2025 \(\) 117.2bn(+14\% y/y),2026\(\) 122.6bn(+5\%).Despite tough y/y comps, we expect customers with secular end- market growth (TSMC, DRAM) to continue spending, offsetting areas of weakness (Intel, TXN).
Positives: TSMC, DRAM, Samsung Foundry. Neutral: NAND, China. Negatives: Intel, TXN

How strong can the 2026 growth drivers be? We see 3 debates on the 2026 growth outlook: 1) DRAM: Can DRAM WFE reaccelerate? 2) TSMC: How high can WFE be? 3) Leading- edge logic: Will we see competition reemerge? We focus on the 2026 growth drivers as the negatives (Intel, TXN) are well understood with both companies giving clear indication that 2026 capex is dependent on customer commitments (Intel) or revenue recovery (TXN). Our view on the growth drivers are as follows:

- DRAM: We model 10% y/y growth as leading edge greenfield should accelerate driven by Samsung and Hynix as memory makers look to offset the HBM die discount.- TSMC: Our analysis of TSMC's semi-annual capex disclosures shows that while spending has returned to near-record levels seen in 1H23, the mix has shifted toward buildings, with equipment investment still muted. It appears TSMC is also pursuing a "shell first" strategy, prioritizing infrastructure build out to support future growth. If equipment spending normalizes back to 80% of capex, we see the possibility of up to 15% upside to equipment spend on a flat \(\) 40bn$ headline capex.- Leading-edge logic: "If" Intel can secure a customer commitment for 14A and recommit to their foundry aspirations and "if" Samsung can secure leading-edge customers beyond Tesla, we would find opportunity to revise up our 2026 & 2027 WFE forecasts considerably, but those are two big "if"s.
We see relatively less variability from NAND and China, with a slight positive bias towards upward revisions for both.
Exhibit 14: Despite tough y/y comps, we expect customers with secular end-market growth (TSMC, DRAM) to continue spending, offsetting areas of weakness (Intel, TXN).

MS View: 2025 \$29.7bn (+1% y/y), 2026 \$32.7bn (+10%). DRAM WFE growth to be led by Samsung and Hynix's leading edge greenfield investment.
The Bull View: Samsung/Hynix/Micron all significantly increase DRAM WFE and CXMT re- accelerates investment.
The Bear View: HBM pricing pressure weighs on margin and dampens Samsung/Hynix/Micron's investment appetite.

HBM to be \(30\%\) of leading edge wafers in 2027. DRAM WFE has reached new highs in 2024- 2025 (approx. \$30bn) on the back of HBM as DRAM makers have had to increase greenfield wafer investment to offset the die discount. We expect this trend to reaccelerate in 2026 led by Samsung and Hynix. We model HBM wafers to be \(30\%\) of leading- edge wafers in 2027, up from \(17\%\) in 2024, but only \(11\%\) of leading- edge bits, up from \(7\%\) in 2024.

2026 to be led by Samsung & Hynix's greenfield. We model industry greenfield wafer adds to increase y/y. Greenfield wafer adds were led by CXMT during 2023- 2025, but we anticipate Samsung and Hynix to drive growth in 2026 as Samsung builds out P4 (Pyongtaek) and Hynix builds out M15X (Cheongju) and adds wafers to M16 (Icheon). Our estimate for 190kwpm of greenfield adds is 2nd highest on record after 2024 (202kwpm) and \(26\%\) above the 2020- 2023 average.

CXMT the X- Factor. CXMT's 2H order intentions have been an enigma for the SPE supply chain, with companies commenting about a lack of visibility. We think this uncertainty is partially attributable to media reports around possible corporate actions later in the year. Our checks indicate that the company hasn't changed their intentions to build a new fab in Shanghai next year, with tools to move in through 2026, but there are production issues from not being able to access US equipment. We model CXMT to increase capacity by 40kwpm in 2026 with 30kwpm coming from the new Shanghai fab.

The "DRAM stock" isn't straight forward. As we highlighted in Semiconductor Capital Equipment: 2Q'25 WFE update, Rethinking our DRAM Thesis (22 May 2025), DRAM spending mix has shifted towards lithography and process control. LAM/AMAT/TEL's share of Core- 5 DRAM WFE has come down from \(60 - 62\%\) in 2020- 2021 to \(52 - 53\%\) in 2023- 2025. Y/Y revenue growth during 2023- 2025 has been directionally similar within the core- 5 equipment players ex- KLA.

Could 2026 look similar to 2024? We see the 2026 set up similar to 2024, when TEL/ ASML/AMAT outperformed as the company's saw an outsized benefit from increased greenfield. We expect 2026 to be greenfield intensive, which is a tailwind for TEL/ASML/ AMAT.

MS View: 2025 \(76.7bn (+13\% y / y)\) , 2026 \(78.2bn (+2\% y / y)\) . We model leading edge logic capex to be up \(7\% y / y\) in 2026, with TSMC and Samsung's growth offsetting Intel's well communicated decline. We expect trailing- edge logic capex to "bottom- out", but we don't model for a recovery.

The Bull View: TSMC accelerates Arizona investment, and WFE mix of capex tracks at \(80\%\) , driving significant \(y / y\) TSMC revenue growth for equipment players. Intel attracts a 14A customer and restart investment.
The Bear View: Consumer electronics weakness (PC, smartphone) lead to TSMC slowing down 2nm build plans, and we see no sign of trailing- edge capex bottoming out.

We know about Intel. TSMC/Samsung should more than offset. We model leading edge logic capex to be up \(7\% y / y\) in 2026, with growth from TSMC (equipment mix increase) and Samsung Taylor offsetting Intel's decline. Our 2026 capex expectations across the major leading edge foundries are as follows:

TSMC \((\) 40.6bn \((+2\% y / y))\) : We expect TSMC to maintain high levels of spending for demand growth across both 2nm and 3nm. Although we model TSMC capex to be up only slightly \(y / y\) , we see equipment spending increase as the foundry reduces spend on infrastructure.

TSMC is taking a page out of Intel's "shell first" playbook. Over the past three quarters, TSMC has ramped capex back up to \(31bn\) in total, well above the \(6bn\) quarterly average during the 4Q23- 3Q24 period. Our analysis of TSMC's capex disclosures shows that while spending has returned to near- record levels seen in 1H23, the mix has shifted toward buildings, with equipment investment still muted. It appears TSMC is pursuing a "shell first" strategy, prioritizing infrastructure build out to support future growth.

Media reports suggest TSMC is currently constructing nine new facilities for 2025. These include specialty fabs in Dresden and Kumamoto, an advanced packaging site (AP7), and six leading- edge fabs: Arizona phase 2 plus five advanced fabs in Taiwan. This reflects both geopolitical pressure (fabs in the US, Europe and Japan) and capacity expansion in high- value segments like advanced packaging.

No constraints to capex growth in years ahead. Still, we think this setup points to rising WFE spend ahead and the cautious tone from TSMC's 2Q25 earnings call that "capex growth is unlikely to surpass revenue growth" should be less of a concern. A back of the envelope analysis suggest that if equipment spending normalizes back to \(80\%\) , we estimate c. \(15\%\) upside to equipment spend on a flat \(\) 40bn$ headline capex. With added cleanroom space and AI trending toward one-third of revenue by FY27, we remain constructive on WFE growth in both '26 and '27.

Samsung (\$6.4bn (+78% y/y)): Samsung achieved successful yield rate at the S3 (Hwasung) and can now start transferring equipment to Taylor for a test run. Along with the equipment transfers, more engineers will arrive at the fab from 2026 for the pre- production with the aim to start volume production in 2027 (9K WPM). For land/property, Taylor 1 is almost complete (local media says 98% as of 1Q25) and currently building fab 2. No details on fab3 assuming nothing has been done yet.

Intel (\$13.2bn (- 21% y/y)): At their JunQ earnings, Intel commented that they won't commit capex towards 14A until they have customer commitments. The company is likely targeting for customer commitments during the 2H 2026 through 1H 2027, with 14A

investment to be accelerated in 2027 in that case. Outside of government intervention, we don't see a strong likelihood that customers will commit to 14A in the 2H of 2025, making revenue contribution from Intel during the 1H of 2026 for the SPE players to be somewhat unlikely.

Trailing edge logic won't come back anytime soon. At their JulQ earnings, AMAT commented that they were seeing "upside in rest of world ICAPS (OctQ)" and that "we did see some green shoots in the quarter. We saw some pickup on the industrial side." We don't think this is indicative of a recovery in trailing edge logic demand, with AMAT's non- China ICAPS revenue \(q / q\) recovery coming from a JulQ where they saw a 76% \(q / q\) decline and their lowest quarterly revenue in the OctQ since 2021. We model TXN's capex to decline from \(\) 5bn\(in 2025 to\) \ \(2bn\) consistent with the company's comments that capex is dependent on revenue levels. We model total logic/discrete capex to decline \(\) 2bn\(y / y\) to \(\) 14bn\((- 13\% y / y)\) with other players not increasing capex enough to offset TXN's decline. We estimate total logic/discrete capex in 2025 to be down 41% from prior peak in 2023 (\)\\(24bn\) and AMAT's FY26 non- China ICAPS revenue to be down 65% from FY23, and while we do see a "bottoming out" during 2025- 2026, we don't model a recovery.

KLA is the undeniable TSMC beneficiary. KLA's TSMC revenue increased 81% y/y in FY25 as the company saw tailwinds from advanced packaging (CY25 \(\) 925mn+\(vs CY24

\(\) 500m+n\$, market share gains (e- beam, mask inspection), and backporting (3nm process control intensity). Our growth expectations are more modest for FY26 (+21% y/y) but we think the company's position at TSMC is going from strength to strength, and is set up for revenue growth beyond 2026.

MS View: 2025 \$39.8bn (- 4% y/y), 2026 \$38.0bn (- 5% y/y). We model Western players' China revenue to decline 13% in 2026 vs 25% growth at local players, driving up localization to 30% (from 16% in 2024).
The Bull View: CXMT, SMIC, and YMTC reaccelerate investment and we continue to see smaller spenders emerge driven by state subsidies and provincial competition.
The Bear View: China's "anti- involution" slows spending as smaller spenders and provincial projects consolidate.

China keeps surprising to the upside. 2025 is the 3rd consecutive year that China surprised to the upside, and we forecast 2025 China WFE of \$39.8bn (- 4% y/y). We had highlighted this dynamic of stronger China demand in Semiconductor Capital Equipment: Mid 2Q'25 WFE Update, China Uptick (1 Jul 2025), and while our overall numbers have come in- line, strength has varied by player.

2025 was China Local & LAM's year. Localization continues to accelerate and we estimate the localization rate increased from 16% in 2024 to 23% in 2025, and we forecast 30% in 2026. We estimate China local players to grow by 5% y/y in 2025 vs Western players to see a 12% revenue decline in the region. The one outlier to Western company's share loss is LAM, where we forecast a 20% y/y revenue increase in 2025 (systems +32% y/y), driven by Hua Hong & Huali's strong investment in the 2H, wins with newer provincial projects, and NAND upgrade spending at Samsung's Xi'an fab.

MS View: 2025 \(10.2bn (+102\% y / y)\) , 2026 \(11.1bn (+9\%)\) . We continue to expect customers to upgrade capacity, but we assume that part of the 2025 strength came at the expense of 2026 as our brownfield assumptions are flat y/y.
The Bull View: YMTC or Samsung reaccelerate NAND investment, driving up spending for the entire industry as competitive dynamics kick in.
The Bear View: Samsung/Hynix/Micron significantly slow down spending as they shift capex \(\) 5\(towards DRAM. Kioxia and YMTC don't materially increase spending.

Upgrades to continue, but we aren't expecting an acceleration. We estimated approx. 1,000kwpm of 128/176- layer NAND capacity across memory makers at the end of 2024, and our prior assumption was for approx. 500kwpm to be upgraded to 200- layers and above during 2025- 2026. We now assume that approx. 660kwpm is upgraded during 2025- 2026 with upgrades balanced between 2025 & 2026. We model little to nonbrownfield ex- China, as upgrades can satisfy the \(53\%\) bit demand growth from 2024 to 2027.

NAND WFE intensity unlikely to surpass \(20\%\) . We aren't overly optimistic on the long- term growth prospects of NAND WFE and model WFE intensity to recover from \(8\%\) in 2024 to \(18\%\) in 2025 but flat line through 2027. We don't expect NAND WFE intensity to return to pre- 2022 levels \((30\% +)\) for 2 reasons: 1) Bit Demand: Y/y bit demand growth tracked above \(30\%\) during 2018- 2022 but has since moderated to mid- teens and we model \(9\%\) in 2025. Although eSSDs are seeing growth from datacenter demand, smartphones just aren't seeing the content growth that they saw during 2018- 2022. 2) DRAM: Hynix/Micron/Samsung have shifted their capex budgets towards DRAM, which has led to DRAM WFE intensity tracking higher vs pre- 2022 but overall memory WFE intensity tracking broadly flat. 3) It's not just layer count growth: Until 2022, NAND makers would pursue layer count growth (i.e. etch/dep investment) as the primary method of increasing bit density but NAND makers are now finding other ways to enable higher bit density. Examples include using lateral shrink by reducing wordline to reduce

area overhead, using CBA (CMOS bonded array, wafer bonding) to individually optimize performance of the CMOS wafers and memory cell wafers to increase interface speed, and logical shrink (QLC) to increase density.

We're all seeing upgrade spend, but it only shifts the needle for LAM. We model LAM/AMAT/TEL/KLA's NAND shipments to increase \(96\% y / y\) in 2025, with the biggest \(y / y\) growth coming from TEL at up \(125\%\) (after declining \(42\%\) in 2024 vs LAM up \(16\%\) ). While NAND growth is encouraging for the industry, the only company where NAND makes up more than \(20\%\) of equipment shipments is LAM (2025 MSE \(24\%\) ), as NAND is sub- \(10\%\) for AMAT/KLA and \(11\%\) for TEL. LAM's share of combined NAND shipments between AMAT/LAM/TEL surpassed \(50\%\) in 2024 ( \(56.3\%\) ), increasing approx. 25ppt over the last decade. We continue to believe LAM will maintain approx. \(50\%\) share of combined shipments due to the majority of spending concentrating on upgrades which favors the incumbent.

Intel recorded non- cash charges of \(\) 797m\(in 2Q25. In the 10Q filing, the company disclosed that:

"results of operations were [...] affected by an impairment charge and accelerated depreciation related to certain manufacturing assets that were determined to have no remaining operational use. This determination was based on an evaluation of our current process technology node capacities relative to projected market demand for our products and services".
In the analyst call the CFO added that:

"This particular write- down that we're isolating [was] mostly was around impairments of equipment. [...] We had some tools that we had bought. They were sitting in assets under construction, as well as we had tools in the line that were older tools, and we took the opportunity since we had an extra - excess amount is we took the newer tools, put them in line, took the older tools out. They had a higher net book value than the value we can get in the open marketplace if we sell them. So we wrote them down to that value and they'll be held in assets held for sale."

This announcement was largely ignored by the market but we believe that this may show up as a headwind for equipment makers. Especially the CFO commentary clarifies the reason for the impairment, to our knowledge previous impairments have not been with the view of selling equipment in the market. Although it appears that some tools may be discarded (subject to accelerated depreciation), it seems that a large(r) chunk of the impairment was to bridge the book value of the tools to their sale value. This implies that the original value of the tools to be sold by Intel is potentially (multiple times) larger than the impairment amount. We don't know the (average) depreciation left on the tools nor Intel's assessment of what would be the fair price in the market today (or even what type of tools Intel is considering to sell), but we can make assumptions:

- We assume that the tools are fully operational and could replace a newly acquired tool- We assume that the c. \(\) 460\(m non - cash impairment is for tools that are adjusted to market value while the tools subject to accelerated depreciation\) \ \(337m\) are assumed to be scrapped- We assume that all the tools were on a linear 8 year depreciation schedule before the write - down (as per Intel's 2023 adjustment)
